<seg id=1> France Against Amending the UN Charter. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Paris. Feb. 14. Staff reporter Lu Wangda Reports: The French Foreign Minister Dumar declared that France will not agree with the demand to amend the UN Charter in order to redistribute the seats of the five permanent member states of the UN Security Council. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> The French foreign Minister issued this statement yesterday in the French National Congress Foreign Affairs Comittee conference. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The Foreign Minister thought that UN was born after the 2nd World War, and France and other five Permenent Member States were all the victorious nations. </seg>
<seg id=5> Although Germany and Italy, as the the defeated nations at that time, have become the democratic countries today, is it enough for them to just recall the past history as past events? </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Here is a report saying that, as today's economically strong nations, in Germany and Japanese, there are repeatedly some people proposing that the seats of the permanent member states of UN Security Council should be redistributed. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> On 11th, the German Foreign Minister Genshier made a speech, in which he hoped that the reunited Germany could have greater effect in the UN and had a bigger saying in making decisions in the UN. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> The Foreign Minister also emphasized that these remarks were unrealistic, and the seats of the permament member states were regulated by the UN Charter, to amend the UN Chart, the member states should reach a consensus on it, and France wouldn't agree to amend the UN Charter. </seg>
</p>
